          <h2 style="font-size: 24px; line-height: 1.2; font-weight: 500">
            Ukraine’s policy reversal
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>
              Summary: Ukraine reversed a bill that offered the government more
              control over two independent anti-corruption bodies.
            </strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Ukraine
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-aug-25-spotlight-h2-4-passed-a-bill?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >passed a bill</a
            >
            restoring the independence of two principal anti-corruption bodies.
            This follows the backlash from abroad and at home over the bill that
            granted the Prosecutor General control of the independent agencies.
            The latest bill introduces mandatory polygraph testing for officers
            to prevent Russian infiltration. World leaders welcomed Ukraine’s
            effort to restore democratic values.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The why:</strong> Young Ukrainians have protested against
            the initial bill's passage, claiming it undermines the powers of the
            independent agencies. They understood that the protection of the
            agency was crucial for their EU integration. The Western partners
            who fund the nation also saw the independence of the agency as
            non-negotiable.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The controversy:</strong> Both bills were passed with
            unanimous support during the parliamentary vote, raising concerns
            over the President’s overreach. Many Ukrainians felt that Andriy
            Yermak, President Zelenskyy's right-hand, influenced the recent
            turnaround. The latest bill was passed after Zelenskyy rejected a
            candidate selected to head the Bureau for Economic Security, an
            agency responsible for investigating economic crimes.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
