            Saudi Arabia’s war on drugs
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 18px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong
              >Summary: Saudi Arabia is disproportionately executing foreigners
              on drug trafficking charges.</strong
            >
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Saudi Arabia had 217 executions in 2025,
            out of which 144 were related to drug trafficking, especially
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-aug-25-analysis-h1-5-captagon?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >captagon</a
            >
            (brand name of the drug fenetylline). The Saudi Crown Prince wants
            to crack down under his “war on drugs” motive. He has increased the
            border checkpoints on highways and at border crossings, and opted to
            double down on arrests and capital punishment. The Saudi public
            security director reported positive results from its fight against
            drugs.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The issue:</strong> The people executed for ‌drug-related
            offences were mainly foreigners from Egypt, Syria, and Pakistan.
            Human rights groups argue these crimes should not carry the death
            penalty and
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-aug-25-analysis-h1-6-undermine-the-reformist-image?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >undermine the reformist image</a
            >
            that the kingdom seeks to project. Experts believe that capital
            punishment is not the resolution to the drug issue, and it can lead
            to further global complications, as seen with the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-aug-25-analysis-h1-7-2018-khashoggi-murder?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >2018 Khashoggi murder</a
            >.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The big picture:</strong> After the fall of Assad’s regime,
            the interim government has effectively neutralized the production of
            captagon. Meanwhile, the actors who profited from drug trafficking,
            like Lebanon, have weakened due to the war in Israel. However,
            analysts suggest that these situations can prevent the trafficking,
            but they wouldn’t end the drug completely.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
