        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The history:</strong> The
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-aug-25-foundations-h1-13-warsaw-uprising?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Warsaw Uprising</a
            >
            was a military operation that started on August 1st, 1944, when the
            Polish Home Army launched the effort to liberate Warsaw from the
            German army. This was part of
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-1-aug-25-foundations-h1-14-operation-tempest?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Operation Tempest</a
            >, aimed at asserting Polish sovereignty before the Soviet army’s
            arrival. The Home Army wanted to liberate the city in a few days.
            However, the fighting lasted over two months.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The resistance:</strong> The uprising was led by the Polish
            government-in-exile in London. About 45,000 Polish Home Army
            fighters encountered 25,000 German troops, with the Polish Army
            capturing most of the city. However, the Germans retaliated with a
            brutal assault, killing 40,000 Polish civilians, and the Nazis took
            the region under siege.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Meanwhile, the Soviet Red Army stayed on the east of the Vistula
            River and did not come to their assistance. Moreover, they refused
            to allow the Western Allies to use Soviet air bases to airlift goods
            to the beleaguered Poles, which compromised the Polish Home Army’s
            defense.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The outcome:</strong> The uprising continued for 63 days
            before ending in surrender on October 2nd. Over 180,000 people,
            mostly civilians, were killed, and Warsaw was systematically
            destroyed. While the uprising ultimately failed, it remains a
            powerful symbol of Polish resistance and national pride. Each year
            on this day, this uprising is honored in Warsaw and other major
            Polish cities with ceremonies and a moment of silence at 5 pm local
            time.
          </p>
